Architecture plan for issues #53 and #54

Repository shape
- Desktop app: Tauri 2 Rust backend under src-tauri/ plus React 19/Vite/TypeScript frontend under src/.
- Main UI shell: src/components/layout/ThreePaneLayout.tsx renders the three-pane workspace and owns the current workspaceRoot restore/update flow.
- Workspace/file UI: src/components/file-tree/FileTree.tsx lists and mutates workspace entries through src/ipc/client.ts.
- Layout sizing: src/state/layoutState.ts owns left/right pane default and minimum widths and persists them in localStorage.
- Styling: src/styles.css contains pane headers, file-tree rows, toolbars, empty states, buttons, and ellipsis/wrapping behavior.
- Tauri command surface: src-tauri/src/main.rs registers Rust commands; src-tauri/capabilities/default.json grants permissions. Existing app data persistence lives in src-tauri/src/store/mod.rs and is exposed through rememberWorkspaceRoot/getWorkspaceState.

Issue #53: Add "Open Folder" workspace directory picker
- Add Tauri dialog support using @tauri-apps/plugin-dialog on the frontend and tauri-plugin-dialog on the Rust side.
- Register the Rust plugin in src-tauri/src/main.rs with the Tauri builder.
- Grant the plugin's directory-open permission in src-tauri/capabilities/default.json; verify the exact permission identifier from the installed plugin version/schema after adding the dependency.
- Add a small frontend abstraction, likely in src/ipc/client.ts or a new src/ipc/dialog.ts, that calls dialog.open({ directory: true, multiple: false }) and normalizes cancellation to null.
- Keep workspace selection state centralized in ThreePaneLayout. Add a handleOpenFolder function that opens the native picker, sets restoreState.workspaceRoot, clears/restores lastOpenFile as appropriate, and lets the existing rememberWorkspaceRoot effect persist it.
- Add an Open Folder action in the left-pane header and a prominent no-workspace empty state button. The no-workspace state should replace the passive "No workspace selected" experience and feed the selected directory into the existing FileTree loading path.
- Browser/Vite preview should fail gracefully because Tauri dialog APIs are unavailable; surface the existing tauri_unavailable style message rather than pretending local FS is usable.

Issue #54: Fix left-pane spacing and awkward item wrapping
- Increase DEFAULT_LAYOUT.leftWidth and MIN_LEFT_WIDTH in src/state/layoutState.ts so the workspace header and file actions have enough room by default and while resizing.
- Make left-pane header content a flex layout with min-width: 0 on the text column, non-shrinking action area, and ellipsis on long absolute workspace paths.
- In FileTree, replace symbolic action labels (+, ++, T, R, x) with discoverable text labels or icon-like labels with clear aria-label/title text. Prefer text such as New file, New folder, Template, Rename, Delete if space allows.
- Allow the file-tree action toolbar to flex-wrap with a gap instead of compressing into unreadable controls.
- Ensure file-tree rows, row labels, nested path containers, and selected text nodes use min-width: 0 plus overflow hidden/text-overflow ellipsis/white-space nowrap so long names do not wrap or overflow.
- Keep accessibility intact: preserve button type, disabled states, aria-labels, selected/current styling, and keyboard-visible affordances.

Dependencies and sequencing
- #53 and #54 touch shared left-pane/header CSS and ThreePaneLayout/FileTree boundaries. Implement #53 first or keep its header action wrapper generic so #54 can refine spacing without reworking behavior.
- #54 is mostly presentational but should account for the Open Folder button added by #53; header action CSS should be reusable for both the workspace picker and existing editor/file controls.
- No database schema changes are needed. Workspace persistence already exists through rememberWorkspaceRoot/workspace_state.
- No new backend IPC command is needed for #53 if using the official Tauri dialog plugin directly from the frontend; backend changes are limited to plugin registration/dependencies/capabilities.

Validation plan
- Run npm install if package-lock changes are required for the dialog dependency.
- Run npm run build for TypeScript/Vite validation.
- Run npm run test:frontend for frontend unit tests.
- Run npm run test:rust after Rust dependency/capability changes.
- Manually verify #53 with npm run tauri:dev because native directory picking cannot be fully validated in Vite browser preview.
